CXLII. ΟΝ ΤΗΕ DEATH OF WILLIAMGORDON, MER- CHANT IN ABERDEEN.

ARGUMENT.

Gordon the merchant has now left the earth: honour and golden piety were ever his companions. Ask not whither he wends his way, what merchan- dise he is in quest of, or what moneys he intends to pay for merchandise. His face is toward Heaven, and God he seeks beyond Ether's battlements. For his wealthy treasure he gives nought but vows. How far he towers above all merchants, whose trading-port is Heaven, whose merchandise is Divinity, whose money of exchange is pious prayers !

CXLIII. ΟΝ GILBERT HAY, SON OF WILLIAM, EARL OF ERROL.

William, the ninth earl, held the earldom from 1631 to 1636. He was son of the Earl Francis who is celebrated in No. XCI.

ARGUMENT.

Errol’s son hardly counts three years, and yet he shows tokens of his native disposition before the time. You notice how in his father's hall he hunts hares, how, though a boy, he summons the hounds with infant's whistle. The greyhounds he delights to view as they go barking round him, and he strokes their backs and face with no timid hand.
